                                "start": 0,
                                "stop": 13.974,
                                "byte_start": 89873,
                                "byte_stop": 145775,
                                "text": "Justice Stevens has the opinion this morning in 05-11284, Abdul-Kabir v. Quarterman in the consolidated case 05-11287, Brewer v. Quarterman."
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "start": 13.974,
                        "stop": 307.827,
                        "byte_start": 145775,
                        "byte_stop": 0,
                        "speaker": {
                            "ID": 15060,
                            "name": "John Paul Stevens",
                            "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/people\/john_paul_stevens",
                            "last_name": "Stevens",
                            "roles": [
                                {
                                    "id": 2704,
                                    "type": "scotus_justice",
                                    "date_start": 188200800,
                                    "date_end": 1277787600,
                                    "appointing_president": "Gerald Ford",
                                    "role_title": "Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States",
                                    "institution_name": "Supreme Court of the United States",
                                    "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/preson_role\/scotus_justice\/2704"
                                }
                            ],
                            "thumbnail": {
                                "id": 32732,
                                "mime": "image\/png",
                                "size": 62101,
                                "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/sites\/default\/files\/john_paul_stevens.png"
                            },
                            "length_of_service": 12611,
                            "identifier": "john_paul_stevens"
                        },
                        "text_blocks": [
                            {
                                "start": 13.974,
                                "stop": 21.136,
                                "byte_start": 145775,
                                "byte_stop": 174510,
                                "text": "These cases come to us from the United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 21.136,
                                "stop": 35.799,
                                "byte_start": 174510,
                                "byte_stop": 233129,
                                "text": "In both cases petitioner\u2019s claim that the former Texas Capital sentencing statute in impermissibly prevented the sentencing jury from giving meaningful consideration to institutionally relevant mitigating evidence."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 35.799,
                                "stop": 41.332,
                                "byte_start": 233129,
                                "byte_stop": 255280,
                                "text": "We agree, and accordingly we reverse judgments of the Court of Appeals in both cases."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 41.332,
                                "stop": 53.537,
                                "byte_start": 255280,
                                "byte_stop": 304077,
                                "text": "Both petitioners were convicted of capital murder, death sentencing one of them presented mitigating evidence of childhood neglect and abandonment and possible neurological damage."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 53.537,
                                "stop": 60.409,
                                "byte_start": 304077,
                                "byte_stop": 331558,
                                "text": "The other presented mitigating evidence of mentally illness, substance abuse and a troubled childhood."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 60.409,
                                "stop": 72.975,
                                "byte_start": 331558,
                                "byte_stop": 381817,
                                "text": "In both cases the Texas State Court denied petitioners relief on direct appeal and post conviction review and the Fifth Circuit denied Federal Habeas Relief."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 72.975,
                                "stop": 85.709,
                                "byte_start": 381817,
                                "byte_stop": 432809,
                                "text": "The cases implicate the same concerns raised repeatedly in this court regarding a jury\u2019s ability to give adequate consideration to capital defendant\u2019s proffered mitigating evidence."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 85.709,
                                "stop": 95.328,
                                "byte_start": 432809,
                                "byte_stop": 471261,
                                "text": "Our first important opinion confining this issue was written by Chief Justice Berger in Lockett v. Ohio in 1978."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 95.328,
                                "stop": 116.067,
                                "byte_start": 471261,
                                "byte_stop": 554226,
                                "text": "His opinion which has been repeatedly followed concluded that sentencing juries must not be precluded from considering, as a mitigating factor any aspect of a defendant\u2019s character or record and any of the circumstances of the offence that may provide a base for imposing a sentence less than death."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 116.067,
                                "stop": 126.937,
                                "byte_start": 554226,
                                "byte_stop": 597693,
                                "text": "A little over a decade later in Penry v. Lynaugh, we reaffirmed that basic rule in the more specific context of Texas capital sentencing jury instructions."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 126.937,
                                "stop": 140.083,
                                "byte_start": 597693,
                                "byte_stop": 650252,
                                "text": "Under the version of the Texas statutes applicable to both of these petitioners at the time of their sentencing, the jury answers to two special issues determine whether the defendant would be sentenced to death."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 140.083,
                                "stop": 158.313,
                                "byte_start": 650252,
                                "byte_stop": 723186,
                                "text": "First, was the conduct of the defendant to cause the death of the deceased committed deliberately and with a reasonable expectation that the death would incur and second is there are probability that the defendant would commit criminal acts of violence who would constitute a continue threat to society."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 158.313,
                                "stop": 170.544,
                                "byte_start": 723186,
                                "byte_stop": 772087,
                                "text": "In affirmative answer to those questions required the jury to impose the death sentence, no matter how persuasive the defendant\u2019s mitigating evidence might be."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 170.544,
                                "stop": 188.615,
                                "byte_start": 772087,
                                "byte_stop": 844394,
                                "text": "In Penry we held that neither of these two instructions known as \u201cthe deliberateness and future dangerousness special issues\u201d provided the jury with a meaningful opportunity to give the fact to the defendant\u2019s mitigating evidence of mental retardation and childhood abuse."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 188.615,
                                "stop": 196.731,
                                "byte_start": 844394,
                                "byte_stop": 876890,
                                "text": "As we explained in that opinion the defendant may present evidence about his background or character or about the circumstances of the crime."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 196.731,
                                "stop": 205.862,
                                "byte_start": 876890,
                                "byte_stop": 913357,
                                "text": "That is either irrelevant to the special issues or that has relevance to defendant\u2019s moral culpability for the crime, beyond the scope of the special issues."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 205.862,
                                "stop": 218.219,
                                "byte_start": 913357,
                                "byte_stop": 962781,
                                "text": "In either of them the Texas special issues do not provide the jury with a mean through expressing this reason to moral response to that evidence in determining, whether the defendant is deserving the death."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 218.219,
                                "stop": 237.317,
                                "byte_start": 962781,
                                "byte_stop": 1039163,
                                "text": "In the case of mitigating evidence like Penry\u2019s where that presented by these petitioners, the evidence may function as a two edged sword because it may diminish the defendant\u2019s blame worthiness for the crime even as it also supports an affirmative answer to one or both of the special issues."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 237.317,
                                "stop": 258.904,
                                "byte_start": 1039163,
                                "byte_stop": 1125576,
                                "text": "Limited only to \u201cthe deliberateness in future dangerousness special issues\u201d the jury may find itself faced with mitigating evidence such as childhood abuse or neglect or mental illness which simultaneously suggests that a defendant will be dangerous in the future but that is moral culpability for the crime does not warrant a death sentence."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 258.904,
                                "stop": 272.749,
                                "byte_start": 1125576,
                                "byte_stop": 1180955,
                                "text": "Rather than correctly applying the reasoning and the rules set fourth in Penry, the Texas State Court in both of these cases held that the Texas special issues did provide for adequate consideration of each defendant\u2019s mitigating evidence."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 272.749,
                                "stop": 283.686,
                                "byte_start": 1180955,
                                "byte_stop": 1224632,
                                "text": "In both cases this conclusion was both contrary to an involved and unreasonable application of clearly established law as determine by this court."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 283.686,
                                "stop": 291.571,
                                "byte_start": 1224632,
                                "byte_stop": 1256188,
                                "text": "Accordingly, we reverse the judgments of the Court of Appeals and remand each case for further proceedings consistent with this opinion."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 291.571,
                                "stop": 299.182,
                                "byte_start": 1256188,
                                "byte_stop": 1286699,
                                "text": "The Chief Justice has filed a dissenting opinion in which Justice Scalia, Justice Thomas and Justice Alito have joined."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 299.182,
                                "stop": 307.827,
                                "byte_start": 1286699,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "Justice Scalia has also filed a dissenting opinion in which Justice Thomas has joined and in which Justice Alito has joined as to Part I."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                ]
            }
        ]
